VI. From the Effect3 in which the main case is, when a word taken from ordinary use draws with it an absurd effect. For if the word be ambiguous, the interpretation is rather to be taken which involves no absurdity. Hence the quibble of Brasidas was not to bo admitted, who, having promised that he would depart from the Boeo- tian territory, denied that that was Boeotiam territory which he occu- pied with his army3 as if the term were to be understood of wal-like possessions, not of the ancient boundaries3 in which sense the com- pact was unmeaning.

VII. Things are conjoined in their origin, or in place. These are eonjoined in their origin which proceed from the same will, al- though uttered at a different place and time3 whence a conjecture is drawn, because in doubtful cases the will is supposed to be in agreement with itself. Thus in Homer, the agreement between Paris and Menelaus, that Helena should be given to tho vietor, must, from what follows, be so expounded‚ that he is victor who kills the other. Plutarch gives the reason, that judges take the view which is least ambiguous.
